column168: Description Of Events

A Memphis spill agent was called to the dangerous goods building for a leaking package. the agent was given a fiberboard box containing a class 3 and it discolored on the bottom.  While investigating the package the agent discovered that one of the five glass bottles inside had broken.  The bottles were wrapped in bubble wrap and inside of a plastic bag. All the contents were placed into a steel salvage package

At 0746 ET, XPO Terminal LBL contacted ERTS to report a spill that occurred inside of a trailer located in Port Allen, LA. The spill consisted of a 55-gallon metal drum of UN2922 "Dabco BL 17", which was punctured at the bottom. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and containment. At 0947 ET, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 25-gallons of product released due to a forklift puncture. The material impacted a 10' x 20' area of the trailer and 10' x 10' area of the concrete lot below. The damaged drum was collected into a 95-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas and collected into two 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

A Memphis spill agent was called to the dangerous goods building for a class 8 in a plastic jerrican. The spill agent noticed that the area around the cap was wet, but the cap was secure. While investigating the jerrican they couldn't find any punctures. It was placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper will be contacted for an amended shipper's declaration.

column168: On January 4, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing UN1993 arrived with a faulty seal and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the loading dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services LC, who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to perform the necessary remedial actions. HCE personnel containerized the damaged drum into one (1) 85-gallon overpack, then utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted surface. All UN1993-impacted material was containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. Both waste drums were staged for disposal by R+L.

column168: The tank car was reported leaking by UPRR train crew employees. Haz Mat Manager Tom Robinson was called for a response. The car had two loose blind flange bolts on the air inlet/vapor valve and the valve was in the closed position when found. The responders tightened the loose flange bolts, and the leak was stopped. We had them open and close the valve to cycle it if it had anything obstructing it from closing all the way. Haz Mat Manager spoke with the shipper and car owner, and they will arrange for a mobile repair crew to test the valve or get an FRA movement approval for it to be delivered to the plant.
Report of tank car leaking liquid from valve cabinet.  Responder found liquid fill valve 1/4 turn open and tie down not sufficiently tight.  valve was closed and release stopped.

On 1-5-2023 at 1230 personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered CTCX733533, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer, Stabilized leaking from vacuum relief valve. The car was isolated and Americas Styrenics were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2023010500192). SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that vapors were being released from the vacuum relief valve. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Kevin Wheat; 832-381-4624. Contractor personnel released pressure and removed the Vacuum Relief Valve and replaced it with a thread plug. SPSI applied 5lbs of nitrogen to the car and checked for leaks.  No leaks detected. An approved OTMA will be required prior to movement to destination. This incident did not require a special switching move.

column168: At 0646 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal LGT. It was reported that approximately 1 gallon of UN1263 Velocity Automotive Products Fast Thinner 2005G was released from a 5-gallon metal drum due to the drum being over-strapped during transit. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3113004. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel were capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. The damaged pail and all spent absorbents were placed into a 10-gallon metal drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 1247 ET, XPO logistics terminal UOR called to report a release of a UN3265 "Prosoco SafEtch" from a 5-gallon poly pail that was punctured by a forklift, impacting the dock floor. ERTS dispatched contractors for containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed all 5- gallons of product released to the dock floor in a 10' x 10' area due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area. The damaged pail & all cleanup debris were then placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Haz Mat Manager got notified from FRA inspector that there was a vacuum relief valve open and hissing on a residue last contained Diesel fuel car in the Avondale train yard. Manager Robinson responded and bled the pressure on the car the release stopped. Manager Robinson put the car in ahold status and is working with the shipper and car owner to have the VRV replaced.

XPO Logistics terminal XAY called in to report a 10-pound spill of UN1495 "Sodium Chlorate" from a 2200-pound supersack caused by a forklift puncture at the previous terminal and impacting trailer floor. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-pounds of product released to the trailer floor in a 10' x 6' area due to a forklift puncture. The damaged sack was patched for shipment on. The released product was collected into a cubic yard box. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On January 12, 2023, at 2212 ET, ERTS was contacted by Landstar personnel in Quanah, Texas regarding the release of approximately 5 gallons of Phosphoric Acid (Phosphoric acid, solution, UN1805).  The release was reportedly due to an emergency hard break in transport and was contained to the trailer and asphalt beneath the trailer.  ERTS dispatched contractors to manage all onsite cleanup activities.  The release was cleaned up using a neutralizing agent, absorbents, hand tools and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum was overpacked and forwarded on to the consignee.  The neutralizer, spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (1) 55-gallon plastic drum for proper disposal.

column168: On January 11, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing hydrogen peroxide was punctured by a forklift and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the concrete loading dock. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental Services (HES) to perform the necessary remedial actions. The crew started by placing the damaged 55-gallon drum into one (1) 85-gallon over-pack. HES personnel utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the surface, then placed all hydrogen peroxide-impacted material in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column168: The package was discovered after the consignee refused the shipment.  Once the package got back to the station the agent heard a distinctive rattling of a spray paint can in the package.  The outer package showed no indications of dangerous goods being contained within.  There was no shippers declaration included.  The employee and their manager opened up the package and found an aerosol spray paint can.  DG Admin advised them to hold the package until further instructed.

XPO Logistics Terminal XCH reported a spill of UN1760 "Rez-Cure EP 624 Part B" from a 55-gallon metal drum due to a forklift puncture resulting in a release impacting their trailer floor. ERTS dispatched a contractor response due to the corrosive nature of the product. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to the trailer floor in a 4' x 8' area due to a puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and collected into a 55-gallon metal drum. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: On January 13, 2023, at 0334 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal LJS experienced a release of UN3265 “Depositrol BL5600”. Due to a forklift puncture a 55-gallon poly drum of product released impacting the trailer floor and concrete lot below. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to the site to perform all cleanup and remediation activities. On January 13, 2023, at 0700 ET, E3 Environmental personnel arrived on site. Contractors confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to an 8' X 15' area of the trailer floor and 5-gallons of product released to a 10' X 10' area of the concrete lot below the trailer due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas. Soda ash and water were then used to neutralize all impacted surfaces. Once cleanup was complete, pH reading inside and outside the trailer showed as 4-5. All impacted absorbents and waste were collected into two 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. All waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0945 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal UMO. It was reported that approximately 2-quarts of UN1133 "Helmistik 1523" released from a 55-gallon metal drum due to a pressure crack towards the bottom of the drum. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3178590. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel were capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. Terminal personnel cleaned the impacted area with absorbents. The damaged drum and all cleanup debris were then placed into a 65-gallon metal drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column25: Veolia North America Regeneration Services LLC
column168: On 1/5/2023 trailer DT314 was loaded with sulfur trioxide at the Veolia Fort Hill Plant in North Bend OH, to be transported on 1/6/2023 to a customer, Pilot Chemical in Middletown OH.  When the trailer departed Fort Hill on 1/6/2023, nothing abnormal was observed by the site, the driver, or site security.  The trailer was being transported by Hazmat Enviromental LLC.   Shortly after the trailer had left the Fort Hill site enroute to the customer, the driver transporting trailer DT314 observed what was described as a haze coming from the covered crash box of the trailer when the driver slowed or stopped.  The driver indicated the haze was nearly unnoticeable while the trailer was in transit. This observation by the driver occurred at approximately 30 minutes after departing Fort Hill.  The driver notified his dispatch and the Fort Hill Plant Site.  The carrier notified Chemtrec per Veolia procedure.  The driver immediately returned to the Fort Hill Site with the trailer.  The trailer was returned to the Fort Hill site at 1010.  The exact time duration of the vapor release is unknown, but based on the driver's observation, it is estimated to have been approximately 45 minutes to 1 hour.  The Fort Hill site observed a light acid mist (vapor / fumes) coming from the WECO Cap of the liquid loading line. Upon further inspection it was determined the gasket sealing the WECO Cap to the liquid line valve spool, was misaligned and did not create a sufficient seal.    This closure (the WECO Cap)  is the secondary closure outside of the loading liquid line valve and outside of the tankers primary closure system.  Sulfur Trioxide residue was present in this spool section, above the liquid line valve, and below the installed WECO Cap.  With the gasket misaligned, it is suspected this allowed that minimal residue to absorb moisture in the air and then omit visible vapor / fumes.  The gasket sealing surfaces were cleaned, inspected, and the gasket replaced at the Fort Hill Plant.  The trailer was re-inspected, and the delivery was later made without incident.
column169: Veolia discovered human error in the installation of the Weco Cap gasket by the Veolia Loading Operator allowed the sulfur trioxide residue behind the Weco Cap to release vapor / fumes.  The incident was leverage with all Fort Hill Site Operators as well as all other Veolia Regeneration plant sites. The specific operator involved in the issue was retrained via 2 different job cycle checks (completed 1/13/2023).  Job Cycle checks consist of re-training by observing the operator perform all task related to properly closing S03 tank trailers to confirm sealing surfaces are clean and gaskets are installed correctly.    Job cycle checks are also being performed on this task (on going).   Additionally, Fort Hill is further reviewing procedures and practices for pressing / cupping Weco gaskets prior to their installation.  Pressing / cupping the Weco gasket is a means of preforming the gasket so it properly seats within the plug and cap.   Though not suspected a cause of this issue, opportunities for improvement may exist and changes may be implemented accordingly.

column168: At 1206 PM ET, XPO Logistics terminal LHO reported a spill that was discovered inside of a trailer located in Houston, TX. column168: On 1/17/2023 at 2038 personnel in the CSXT Corbin Yard discovered GATX 94659, a loaded tank car of crude sulfate turpentine leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and Domtar and the National Response Center were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2023-01-17-00304. Marion Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a product leak coming from the liquid valve packing gland. The packing was missing two nuts that hold the packing into place. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Brain Kozlowski, 715-886-7310. Contractor personnel installed the two packing gland nuts, tightened them down, and wiped the car down. The leak was secured was held until an OTMA could be submitted. This incident did require a special switching move.

On 1-18-23 at 1130 personnel in the CSXT Edgewood Yard discovered GATX200407, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine leaking vapors from the manway. The car was isolated and Georgia Pacific/Leaf River Cellulose were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2023011800157). Hepaco LLC, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapors were being released from the manway. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tom Davidson and 404-376-9550. Contractor personnel opened manway and found that gasket was damaged, Hepaco installed a new manway gasket and tool tightened manway safety bolts. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.

column168: On 1/7/2023 at approximately 0730, Dangers Goods Administration received a call from Employee 625959 at the ramp facility in Denver, reporting an undeclared resin spill. The shipment was a 23-piece shipment of resin in plastic drums, each holding 7.57 liters. Spillage was discovered on the aircraft floor. One of the drums was discovered cracked across the bottom, resulting in leakage. Further investigation and the enclosed SDS revealed that the shipment shipped undeclared being void of the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork in accordance with IATA Regulations. The aircraft floor was cleaned and cleared to return to service. The shipment is being held pending an FAA investigation.

column168: On 1/12/2023 at approximatley 1200, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 986791, at the hub facility in Oakland, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consists of 27 fiberboard boxes, each two plastic bags inside.  Each bag holds 2 cans of paint.  One of the boxes emitted a strong odor, gaining the attention of the agent.  Further investigation revealed that 2 cans appeared to be dented inside one of the bags and drops of paint were discovered inside of the bag.  The outer package appeared damp in one corner, but no other physical damage was present.  The shipment was placed in a salvage drum and awaits an amended shipper's declaration to be returned to the shipper.

On January 13, 2023, ERTS was contacted by MC Tank Transport personnel in Chattanooga, Tennessee requesting facilitation of the cleanup of a release of a Sodium Bisulfite solution (Bisulfites, aqueous solution, n.o.s., UN2693, 8, III) from (1) 5,000-gallon tanker.  ERTS then dispatched contractors to manage all onsite cleanup activities.  Following contractor arrival and assessment of the involved cargo, it was determined that approximately 20 gallons of sodium bisulfite solution was released to a 2’ by 2’ area of gravel beneath the tanker. The release was reportedly due to a leak from the CTMV sleeve. Contractors cleaned up the release using absorbents, hand tools and the proper PPE.  The spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (3) 55-gallon plastic drums. The waste drums were then transported offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

column168: On January 04, 2023, Schneider Bulk Carriers contacted ERTS to report a four-gallon spill of regulated UN1993 "Olefin Sulfide" combustible liquid n.o.s that was released during transit. The caller stated that the release came from one liquid bulk tank as a result of mechanical failure and impacted the inside flooring of Trailer #21463 located at the Weight Station of (MM#26) I-30, Hope, AR. Lonestar arrived on site and located the tanker and approximately 4 gallons spilled with only 3 or 4 oz on the ground in a 6" area. The majority of the spill was on the back of the tanker.  Lonestar advised that when wiping the tanker, it was smearing around, according to the SDS the product is insoluble, so the crew wiped down the sides of the tanker as well as the brakes and tires with brake cleaner and degreaser.  One drum of contaminated rags and pads was generated and properly disposed of on January 17, 2023, at Pleasant Oaks Landfill in Mt Pleasant, TX.

column168: XPO Logistics Terminal UBF experienced a UN3266 Corrshield NT4200 release from a 30-gallon poly drum due to a fault cap. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5-cup of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the drum lid due to a faulty cap. The material was transferred into a new 55-gallon poly drum for shipment on. The damaged drum was placed into a 55-gallon poly drum and all cleanup debris placed into a 30-galon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Terminal ULV contacted ERTS to report that their terminal had a 3-gallon spill of regulated UN1823 "Pels Caustic Soda Beads" that was released from a 55-gallon metal drum during the unloading process. The caller stated that terminal personnel punctured the container with a forklift. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 15-pounds of product released to a 15' x 6' area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. The damaged drum was containerized into a 95-gallon poly overpack. All released product and cleanup debris was collected into a 5 gallon and 15 gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XEN experienced a UN1824 Gardobond Additive H 7212 release from a 275-gallon poly tote due to a puncture. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 9-gallons of product released to a 6' x 6' area of the dock floor due to a puncture. The product was transferred into a new poly tote. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all spent absorbents and cleanup debris into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal LFW experienced a UN3266 "ZEP X-203" release from a 275-gallon poly tote. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 80-gallons of product released to a 7' by 20' area inside the trailer and a 7' by 53' area outside the trailer on the concrete lot due to a puncture. The product was transferred into a new tote. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into nine 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: On 9 Jan 2023 Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from their RT station in Hebron KY. During normal sort procedures a box was offered to the spill clean up specialist which had a stain on the side of the fibreboard box indicating a spill within. Before Further inspection, it was noted the stain on the package smelled of gasoline or some other sort of stringent cleaner. Further inspection of the package found what appeared to a machine part of some kind. The part was wrap in a plastic moisture barrier. Bubble wrap was reported used as dunnage, and PIG mats were placed on the bottom of the box. A call to the shipper from DG Admin confirmed this was a used fuel pump from an aircraft which was out for repair. The fluid was reported by the shipper as jet fuel. This package was not marked nor labeled to inform others of the dangerous good in apparatus contained in the package. Package has been held at the station pending a FAA investigation. i

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED SLIGHTLY STAINED IN APPEARANCE BY AN AUDITOR IN THE HAZ-MAT AUDIT AREA. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE CONTACTED THE DMP. WITHIN 2 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE SIDE WALL OF THE CARTON. THE INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A CORRUGATED PARTITION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal NML experienced a release from a box containing (12) 1-quart poly bottles. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-quarts of product released to a 5' x 5' area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged box, impacted pallet wood, and impacted absorbents were collected into two 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal UWY experienced a release of UN3378 Provox C from a 55-pound paper bag. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-pound of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the dock floor due to improper loading. The damaged bag and released product were collected into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package arrived at station and found wet and leaking during unload. Package was placed into a hazmat tote and bag. Upon inspection of the package 1 of the bottles was punctured and leaking its contents at the bottom of the bottle. Other bottle is fine. DescribePack: 1 of 2 bottles was found leaking fluids from the bottom corner and soaked the outer package. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Neutralizer was used to cover spill and hazmat materials were placed in a hazmat tote and bag.

SequenceEvent: The cap of the bottle was loose, leading to a partial amount of the enclosed liquids in the plastic container to escape onto the inside of the outer fiberboard box. DescribePack: The fiberboard of the box was soiled and cannot hold the weight of the merchandise. SequenceEvent: The cap on the bottle was loosened, leading to a partial escape of the enclosed liquids. DescribePack: Loose cap DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Both the bottle and the package were placed in a lined tote and forwarded to the hazmat cage for processing.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package was found wet and open after it had just gone down chute 69 in Load 6 of RORS 622. This caused a spill inside and also outside the trailer. The spill was immediately cleaned up and the package was isolated from the rest of the staff. DescribePack: 2 bottles of the bleach inside the box had their caps off, along with their seals torn. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Package was taken to the Hazmat cage for isolation and processing.

SequenceEvent: the package was found during the OTP sort and was place inside the Hazmat Cage for inspection. column168: SequenceEvent: A package handler notified QA that there was a leaking hazmat on a trailer. QA retrieved the damaged hazmat and assessed the package. QA found there was a loose cap and that hazardous solution leaked out of package making the box damp. No amount of hazardous material leaked onto trailer or floor, and no PPE cleaning materials were used besides gloves for handling. The ethanol solution was contained in four   one-gallon plastic jugs. Outer packaging was a cardboard box. There was no inner packing material. Package was found at 7:30 AM on 1/12/23. DescribePack: Cap came loose on jug and a small amount of liquid leaked and made packaging wet. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: Package was put in a red tote lined with blue bag.

SequenceEvent: When package was in transit driver noticed the package was wet. Driver placed package inside a tote and gave it to QA for inspection. SequenceEvent: I was notified that there was a hazmat in unload that came out of trailer with wet at the top and part of a bottle protruding out of fibreboard box. column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: SequenceEvent: THE HAZMAT WAS BROUGHT OVER TO THE DESIGNATED TRUCK TO BE LOADED ONTO THE ROUTE  FROM THE TRAILER BY A PACKAGE HANDLER WHO IS ASSIGNED TO RUN NON-CONVEYABLES TO THE CORRECT AREAS OF THE BUILDING BY HAND. THE PACKAGE HANDLER LOADING THE TRUCK ON THE VAN LINE NOTICED A SMALL BLEACHED LOOKING SPOT LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND DID NOT CONTINUE LOADING IT. QA WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND HAZMAT WAS BROUGHT OVER TO THE APPROPRIATE PROCESSING AREA. THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE IN VAN, ON TUGGER TRAIN OR IN THE TRAILER. THE LEAK DID NOT REACH THE POINT OF SPILLING OUTSIDE OF THE BOX. DescribePack: THE PACKAGE ITSELF WAS NOT AT FAULT. THERE IS NO VISIBLE DAMAGE TO THE OUTER PACKAGING. INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE THERE WERE 4 1-GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF CORROSIVE CONTAINED IN PLASTIC BAGS. THE CAPS WERE TAPED. THE EXTRA SPACE WAS FILLED WITH HAZMATPAC ABSORBENT VERMICULITE THAT ABSORBED MAJORITY OF THE SPILLED LIQUID. UPON INSPECTION OF THE PLASTIC 1-GAL BOTTLES, THE CAPS WERE ALL IN TACT. 1 OF THE 4 BOTTLES HAD LESS LIQUID AND CORROSIVE INSIDE OF THE PLASTIC BAG. THE CAP TO THIS BOTTLE WAS SECURE. IT SEEMS LIKE THERE IS A SMALL CRACK IN THE LINING OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLE THAT IS NOT EASILY VISIBLE. IT APPEARS THAT MAYBE FROM THE TEMPERATURE CHANGE AFTER BEING IN TRANSIT FROM CALIFORNIA TO TENNESSEE, THE WEATHER CHANGED SIGNIFICANTLY AND POSSIBLY IMPACTED THE STRUCTURE OF THE PLASTIC GALLONS THROUGH HEAT EXPANSION AND WEATHER VARIATION. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE ASBORBENT VERMICULITE INSIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED THE RELEASE OF THE SPILL IMMEDIATELY.

DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PAINT CANS WERE BOTH IN PLASTIC BAGS, HOWEVER THE ONE THAT SPILLED DID COME OUT OF THE PLASTIC BAG AND SPILL ONTO THE PAINT CAN THAT DID NOT SPILL. THEY WERE BOTH PLACED IN A LINED DRUM AND CLOSED UP SO THAT NO FURTHER FUMES WERE EMITTED.

column168: On 1/12/2023 at approximately 1200, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 986791, at the hub facility in Oakland, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consists of 27 fiberboard boxes, each two plastic bags inside.  Each bag holds 1 can of paint.  One of the boxes emitted a strong odor, gaining the attention of the agent.  Further investigation revealed that both cans appeared to be dented inside of the bags and drops of paint were discovered inside of the bag.  The outer package appeared damp in one corner, but no other physical damage was present.  The shipment was placed in a salvage drum and awaits an amended shipper's declaration to be returned to the shipper.

WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. THE INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF 4" OF FOAM PEANUTS AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: January 05, 2023, DHL Supply Chain called in to request assistance with a 55-gallon spill of UN3082 "LESCO Three-Way Selective Herbicide" from a 55-gallon plastic drum caused by a forklift puncture.  Miller arrived onsite and confirmed 100ft by 12ft stretch of the parking lot was impacted, a small puddle in front of the truck and a 12ft by 8ft area inside of the trailer floor was impacted by the release.  DHL personnel used boom and protected the onsite drain from being impacted prior to the contractor arriving.  Miller used granular absorbents to collect the released material.  All onsite work was completed on January 06, 2023, 1–55-gallon DM containing liquid, and 3–55-gallon DMs containing impacted absorbents were generated from this incident. Waste still pending disposal.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On 1/07/2023 Veolia employees were loading drums into a trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY facility when an employee inadvertently punctured a 55 gallon plastic drum when it was being loaded on a trailer. The puncture was caused by a drum cart while moving it onto a trailer in the 10-day transfer area at the Veolia office. The employees immediately noticed the leak and quickly set the drum down to keep it from leaking more by placing it on its side to prevent it from leaking further.  The punctured drum was overpacked into an 851A2 salvage drum to continue transportation to the ultimate disposal facility.     The drum leaked approximately 1/2 gallon of class 6.1 III waste Trichloroethylene. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the drum was over-packed into an appropriate 85 gallon salvage drum along with the clean up materials. The duration of release is anticipated to be about 1 minute due to the small hole and quick response.  The drum was still substantially full after the leak occurred.
column169: On 1/07/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the incident. The results of the safety manager's investigation is that a newer employee was assisting another employee with the shipment. The trailer was being filled with containers and the employee was immediately aware that they had poked a hole in the drum. Human error did have a role in this incident. The employee who loaded the trailer was reminded to be more careful when loading drums with a drum cart. Also we have made some provisions to have additional employees present from the facility to assist in case of an emergency.

column168: On January 9, 2023, Dana Companies contacted ERTS regarding an Organic Peroxide release that occurred at 0702 ET near the intersection of West 47th Street and South Water St. in Wichita, KS. It was advised that 50-200 gallons of product released to a ditch line near a railroad crossing due to a valve being left open.  At 1048 EST, Haz-mat Response arrived onsite and confirmed 100 gallons had released from the tanker for approximately one mile in distance. It was advised the 1 mile of impact had been tracked through and appeared to be mostly dried up. The primary impact area had product pooled approximately 150ft in front and behind the trailer. The crew began applying absorbents. Haz-Mat Response advised there was no evidence of product in any drains. Haz-Mat completed operations and departed the site with (8) eight 55-gallon poly drums of impacted clay.  Waste is stille pending disposal.

column168: On January 26, 2023 at approximately 04:00 AM CDT a CN mechanical employee observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve cap of rail car # GBRX 703550 (Load / UN 1987 / Class 3 / PG II / Alcohols N.O.S.) while performing an inbound train inspection at the CN Waterloo Yard in Waterloo, Iowa.  The railcar was isolated, all required notifications made. CN Response Team responded to the location from Gary, Indiana.  The cause of release is determined to be due to debris or an object trapped in the bottom outlet valve preventing a complete seal of the valve seat allowing product to fill and leak out of the improperly secured bottom outlet valve securement cap (BOV cap was not fully tightened.  The BOV cap was tightened approximately 1/2 turn which stopped the leak. The BOV handle was then cycled to the open and closed position 5 times to free any possible obstruction from the valve seat. The BOV cap was completely removed and observed for any additional leakage for 10 minutes. There was no further indication of leakage and the BOV cap was re-applied utilizing a 36" pipe wrench. The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated, then released onto destination.

column168: A Harcros driver walked around a loaded tanker and did a pre trip check. He looked up at the top and saw the vent valve closed. He did not climb up and check the dome although the checklist indicated the dome bolts had been checked. The driver left Harcros' property and drove to the end of the street and stopped. Then, he made a right tum and started up a hill. He looked back and saw product running out the dome lid area drain hose. Driver immediately pulled to the side of road, climbed up and noticed the dome was not tight. The driver called Harcros' office and the Operations Manager drove less than a mile to the incident site to assess the situation. The spilled material was promptly cleaned up.

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: On 1/26/2023 at 2:30pm Environmental and Hazmat became aware of a leaking tank car in the Shreveport Yard. Mechanical personnel reported the TILX 284448, Crude Oil/Load, to be leaking from the top manway area.  KCS mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to investigate and mitigate the leak. Upon inspection, the contractor identified the liquid line valve to be in the open position with secondary closure plug less than tool tight. Resulting release was approx. 1 gallon.  Corrective action taken was to move liquid line valve to the closed position and secure the secondary closure plug to a tool tight state.  Once car was secured it was released back into transportation.  File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a 'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. (Please direct your root cause Investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.
column198: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY

column168: 04:51 am - Employee noticed a liquid leak coming from between the flange of the storage tank and the gauge. he notified manager immediately and operations were shut down. 05:17 am - Manager reached out to safety department for further instructions and the tank was locked out and tagged out in the meantime.Liquid stopped leaking from the tank and there was a slight vapor leak. 8:15 am - Once deemed safe to operate, other tanks were closed and the tank with the leak was opened so that the tank could be emptied of liquid propane Tank emptied out within two days and locked out. All remaining propane was flared off after Miami-Dade FD approved prior to repair and remained locket out. 2/9/2023 - The gauge and gasket were replaced and the investigation was finalized.
column169: We have replaced the old gauge and gasket with an entirely new assembly to improve the packaging.  We will continue visual and audible checks for leaks at the plant as part of our daily pre and post inspections.  We will also implement semi-annual leak tests to our procedures on the gauges of this storage tank as well as the others that we have on property in order to more proactively monitor to leaks at these tanks.

column168: Video review shows Mr. Lowell travelling at the posted speed limit. Entering a slight curve in the road, Mr. Lowell continues to drive straight crossing over fog line and dropping off of asphalt shoulder onto dirt shoulder. At this time, he tries to correct to the left which caused trailer to tip over and pulls truck and trailer onto their side striking the guard rail. Most of load was lost at accident scene Clifton Fire Department cleaned up the ANPAN on the roadway Emergency Environmental Services(EES) responded to the scene for final cleanup. They had to leave the product in place, which was approved by ADOT, they required a Traffic Plan from ADOT to complete the cleanup. Phase 1 of clean up was on Friday, January 13, 2023 Phase 2 of clean up on Wednesday, January 21, 2023 Samples were taken to ensure proper cleanup. Root Cause, Human Error: The driver stated he was distracted by the scenery, he was not pay attention to the road
column169: Terminal manager had discussion with driver about maintaining focus and getting distracted while driving a commercial motor vehicle. column168: At 00:30 on 1/6/2022, Kansas City Southern Railway's(KCS) Environmental& Hazmat Department was notified of an Ammonia odor in the KCS Port Arthur, TX rail yard. A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate the odor. Upon arrival, responders identified SHPX 221270 as the Ieaking tank car. Responders dawned proper PPE before ascending the car. Once on top of SHPX 221270, responders found the A-slde liquid valve less than tool tight and the A-side liquid valve plug was also less than tool tight. Estimated release was 3 gallons. The liquid valve and the plug were both secured tool tight. Once secure, the rail car was released back Into transportation. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the tlme offiling. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package Is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal Injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adJacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. column168: On 1/17/2023 at around 10:49 AM, Kansas City Southern Railway's(KCS) Environmental& Hazmat Department was made aware by KCS Mechanical that a loaded Argon car, BOCX 3038, was Ieaklng from the fittings cabinet while in the KCS Shreveport, LA railyard. A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to mitlgate the leak. Upon arrival, responders observed a small drlp from BOCX 3038's left side cabinet. The cabinet security seal was removed and cabinet door opened. Ice build up was observed on V-29 Pressure Build Vapor return valve assembly, V-9 Manual Vent Valve assembly, and the Road Relief Isolation Valve. the Road Relief valve was observed in the open position with a small vapor leak emanating from the valve stem/packing nut assembly. The Road Relief isolation valve packing nut was secured tool tight via wrench application and the valve handle was actuated to the closed position. Water was applied to defrost all valves and fittings. After defrostlng and approximately 10 minute observation, no further leaks were observed. Responders applied zip ties to the valve handles to secure them In the closed position. To ensure the car had been properly secured, BOCX 3038 was evaluated the following morning. The car was determined to be ventlng normally without defect. Once securement was verified, the car was released back into transportation. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best Information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.

column168: 1/25/2023 - Discovered a leak at the internal valve while it was in the open position. The attempt to tighten the packing nut (gasket) on the internal valve failed, so it was turned off which stopped the leak completely. The system was left off and was locked out and tagged out to ensure no one could re-energize the liquid line. The pnuematic line going to the internal valve was also disconnected to ensure that the acuator could not be filled back with air.  1/30/2023 - System was briefly unlocked and monitored while the remaining liquid was withdrawn from the tank.  2/8/2023-2/10/2023 - Contractor flared off the remaining vapor in the tank and replaced the leaking internal valve with a brand new internal valve.  When replacing, it was noted that the packing inside the valve had been damaged by being tightened to many times. The facility had leaks in the past that they stopped by tightening the packing, but did not replace the internal valve.
column169: An improved procedure has been put in place to that the proper steps are taken to repair valves at the facility in the future.  In addition to this new procedure, the facility did inspect all other internal valves for leaks, and to ensure proper function.

column168: 2 Super Sacks containing Chromium waste from Eagle Window and Door were accepted into our transportation network. These bags had been previously stored in an unprotected area where they were exposed to the elements, ie., snow or rain. These water permeated the mesh bags and wetted the material inside. The result was approximately 2 quarts of the solid Chromium material being released as an aqueous solution due to the permeation of the water.
column169: The account manager for the generator was informed of the deficient storage of the containers allowing rain and snow to accumulate and permeate the Super Sacks resulting in the material becoming saturated and leaking from the container. column168: On January 24, 2023 at approximately 01 :13 a.m., a Brenner Oil Company unit (tractor/trailer) left the pavement due to icy conditions while traveling northbound on US 131. In the course of incident, the tractor disconnected from the tanker trailer and left the tractor upright while the tanker trailer came to rest on its side in a low-lying area to the east of the unpaved shoulder area. The accident and rollover of the tanker trailer resulted in the release of 5,157 gallons of unleaded gasoline from several damaged compartments onto the unpaved areas within the highway right-of-way (ROW) to the east of US 131 NB. Numerous fire departments, the Michigan State Police (MSP), the Michigan Department of Transportation (MOOT), and Brenner personnel responded to the incident. GFL Environmental (formerly Northern A-1) provided environmental incident response and mobilized to minimize the spread of spilled gasoline, place sorbents, etc. The fuel remaining in the tanker trailer was pumped into another vehicle and properly transported away. Soil excavation activities began on January 24, 2023, with contaminated soils temporarily stockpiled nearby until appropriate off-site disposal could be arranged. Surface water run-off and potentially impacted groundwater is being removed and staged in frac tanks, pending analytical results, after which proper management will occur. Excavated soils are being transported to the Central Sanitary Landfill in Pierson, Michigan, and excavated areas are being backfilled with clean fill. The environmental response work is being overseen by personnel from the Michigan Department of Environmental, Great Lakes, and Energy (EGLE) and is currently ongoing.

column168: After the trailer loading was complete the operator used plant air pressure to blow out the liquid lines from the loading stand to the trailer. As the air surgec through the lines the driver began walking to hose towards the trailer to make sure all liquid was purged from the loading hose. Pressure built quickly in the trailer due the small amount of vapor space in the trailer and 120psig air pressure from the plant supply line blowing out the hose. When the trailer pressure reached 25 PSIG the relief lifted to vent pressure from the trailer. The trailer was in a sloped containment which caused the relief valve to be in the liquid phase causing a liquid release of product. As soon as the driver and operator heard/saw the release the air pressure was shut off to the hose and the inlet valve on the trailer was closed. This immediately stopped the release and the relief valve reset without issue.
column169: Prior to loading trailer we need to verify that the trailer is empty and that the loading meter is correctly calibrated to not overfill the trailer. Trailer should not exceed 95% on liquid level gauge. Pressure should be monitored whiled blowing lines clear of liquid.

column168: At 00:30 on 1/6/2023, Kansas City Southern Railway's (KCS) Environmental & Hazmat Department was notified of an Ammonia odor in the KCS Port Arthur, TX rail yard. A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate the odor.  Upon arrival, responders Identified SHPX 221270 as the leaking tank car. Responders dawned proper PPE before ascending the car. Once on top of SHPX 221270 , responders found the A-side liquid valve less than tool tight and the A-side liquid valve plug was also less than tool tight. Estimated release was 3 gallons. The liquid valve and the plug were both secured tool tight. Once secure, the rail car was released back Into transportation.  File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a 'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: On January 5th, 2023, at 0326 personnel in the CSXT Radnor Yard discovered GATX216232, a residue tank car of hydrochloric acid leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Jones Hamilton, Nashville Fire and EMS, TEMA, and NRC were notified CHEMTREC Report #2023-01-05-00033.  Ryan Godsey CSXT hazardous materials manager, and Marion Environmental Inc., a CSX response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found an active vapor release coming from the fittings plate and tank car connection. 20 of 20 fittings plate bolts were found to be less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Sam Perras, 419-666-9838, sperras@jones-hamilton.com. Contractor personnel secured the 20 fittings plate bolts and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured, and the car is currently being held at the terminal until the tank car is properly cleaned & purged, and the fittings plate bolts are properly torqued to manufacturer’s spec. This incident did not require a special switching move.  One CSX employee did have EMS evaluate him and he did go to the hospital. After being evaluated at the hospital he was discharged with no facility administrated medications.

column168: THE SINCLAIR TRUCK DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING SOUTH ON THE MOUNTAIN VIEW CORRIDOR. WHEN THE TRUCK AN DRIVER ARRIVED AT 3500 SOUTH, THE LIGHT WAS GREEN FOR THE SINCLAIR TRUCK TO PROCEED THROUGHT THE INTERSECTION. A SUV (SMALL JEEP), MADE A LEFT-HAND TURN FROM THE NORTHBOUND LANE DURING A “RED LIGHT” FOR THE TURN LANE AND WAS STRUCK BY THE SINCLAIR TRUCK. THE TRUCK WAS FORCED TO ITS RIGHT, ROLLED, AND HIT A CONCRETE WALL. THE TRACTOR IMPACTED THE CONCRETE WALL AND THE DRIVER WAS KILLED WHEN THE TRUCK IMPACTED THE WALL.  THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER WAS CRUSHED AND A HOLE WAS TORN IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER BY THE CONCRETE WALL. WHEN THE TRAILER ROLLED THE CONCUSSION OF HITTING THE CONCRETE AND THE SCRAPING AS IT CONTINUED DOWN ROAD OPENED UP MANY SMALLER HOLES IN THE SIDE OF THE TANK AND IT LEAKED. WEST VALLEY FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND FIRST ATTENDANT TO THE DRIVER AND CONFIRMED THAT THE DRIVER HAD NOT SURVIVED THE CRASH. THE WVC FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN TENDED TO CONTROLLING THE FLOW OF THE DIESEL TO TRY AND AVOID STORM DRAINS AND DIRT AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE BY KEEPING THE DIESEL UP ON THE CONCRETE. AN AMOUNT OF DIESEL DID GO INTO THE STORM DRAIN AND FOLLOWED THE DRAIN FOR ABOUT A QUARTER OF A MILE.  SINCLAIR TRUCKING CALLED IN ENVIROCARE TO DO THE CLEANUP. ENVIROCARE IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWED THE DIESEL IN THE STORM DRAIN UNTIL THEY GOT TO RETENTION AREA, AND THEY SET UP ABSORBENT BOOMS AND BUILT DAMS FROM SOIL TO STOP THE PROGRESS OF THE DIESEL.  THE CITY OF WEST VALLEY BROUGHT IN LOADS OF DIRT ALONG WITH THE UTAH DOT AND USED IT TO DAM UP AND CONTROL THE FLOW.
column169: THE CRASH WAS CAUSED BY A PASSENGER VEHICLE THAT RAN A “RED LIGHT” AND COLLIDED WITH THE SINCLAIR TRUCK AND DRIVER. THE SINCLAIR DRIVER DIED BECAUSE OF THE ACTIONS OF THE DRIVER OF THE PASSENGER VEHICLE.

column168: CO-ALLIANCE VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST ON US 12 (4-LANE HIGHWAY W/MEDIAN) IN THE RIGHT LANE. MARATHON VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US 12 IN THE RIGHT LANE. CO-ALLIANCE DRIVER HAD A MEDICAL EVENT AND LEFT THE EAST BOUNDS LANES DRIVING INTO THE MEDIAN AND INTO THE WEST BOUND LANES OF US 12 UNTIL STRIKING THE MARATHON VEHICLE HEAD ON. BOTH DRIVERS WERE DECEASED AS A RESULT OF THE CRASH.  THE CO-ALLIANCE VEHICLE WAS A MC 331 PROPANE DELIVERY STRAIGHT TRUCK. AT IMPACT, THE TANK BROKE FREE FROM THE CHASSIS. THE HOSE WAS RIPPED FROM THE SYSTEM AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 100 LBS. OF PROPANE. ALL OTHER SAFETY DEVICES ON THE CARGO TANK FUNCTIONED PROPERLY. THE HOSE RELEASE WAS LESS THAN 30 MINUTES.  MC 331 CARGO TANK SUFFERED A SIGNIFICANT DENT, BUT THE CARGO TANK DID NOT LEAK OR FAIL. CO-ALLIANCE HAS TAKEN THE TANK OUT-OF-SERVICE AND IS DONATING THE CARGO TANK TO THE AREA FIRE DEPARTMENTS FOR A TRAINING MODULE.  GENERAL VEHICLE FLUIDS WERE CLEANED USING ABSORBANT PADS AND LOOSE ABSORBANTS. NO FIRE OR EXPLOSION.
column169: THE CO-ALLIANCE DRIVER WAS 35 YEARS OLD AND HAS A VALID AND CURRENT MEDICAL EXAMINERS CARD. WE BELIEVE THIS WAS AN UNFORTUNATE SEVERE HEALTH EVENT THAT LEAD TO THE CRASH.  THE SAFETY SYSTEMS ON THE MC331 CARGO WORKED AS DESIGNED, SO THE LOSS WAS LIMITED TO THE PROPANE IN THE HOSE.
